>In "Thinking Fast and Slow," Daniel Kahneman metaphorically divides the mind into two parts.

>>1.  System 1
>>2.  System 2

> System One does more of thinking.  It's fast.  It's often wrong, but it doesn't care as long as the mind survives the day.  System 1 is that part of the mind that others have called "intuitive."  Fast, and very good at many, many things.

> System Two is slow, uses up a lot of energy; we rather not go there.  This is "rational" thought.

> While System 1 thinking might be beautiful while your walking through the hills or watching a movie, for science to work, we need to rely heavily, also exclusively, on System 2 thinking, which, as I said, is hard 
